<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Panamanian, Costa Rican Presidents Discuss Joint Antidrug </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Panamanian, Costa Rican Presidents Discuss Joint Antidrug </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
Efforts 

<F P=102>   PA2205122494 Panama City EL PANAMA AMERICA in Spanish 21 May 
94 p A1 </F>

<F P=103> PA2205122494 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City EL PANAMA AMERICA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Arnulfo Barroso Watson] </F>
  [Text] Costa Rican President Jose Maria Figueres and 
Panamanian President-elect Ernesto Perez Balladares met 
yesterday in San Jose and agreed to join efforts during their 
respective administrations to fight drug trafficking and to 
adopt measures to improve their commercial relations. 
  Perez Balladares traveled to Costa Rica with Foreign 
Minister-designate Gabriel Lewis Galindo on an invitation by 
fellow Social Democrat Jose Maria Figueres, with whom he met for 
about one and one-half hours. 
  In a news conference at the Costa Rican Presidential Palace, 
Figueres and Perez Balladares said they talked about four 
specific issues: bilateral trade, social investments at the 
common border, creation of a mixed-bilateral commercial 
association, and the struggle against drug trafficking. 
  Both presidents agreed the sovereignty of their respective 
nations is violated when they are used by drug traffickers for 
their illicit trade. 
  "We agreed to carry out efforts, in a decisive and 
definitive 
manner, to control drug smuggling as a mutual responsibility," 
Figueres stated. 
  Meanwhile, Perez Balladares said the issue of drug 
trafficking is fundamental. He affirmed that the struggle 
against drug trafficking may result in the creation of liaison 
and joint cooperation offices, not only with the United States, 
but also with all countries that feel the need to cooperate in 
this matter. 
  Figueres' National Liberation Party and Perez Balladares' 
PRD 
[Democratic Revolutionary Party] assisted each other during the 
elections in their respective nations. Both presidents were 
classmates at the University of Notre Dame in the United States. 
  The presidents expressed their interest in building a 
permanent commission formed by the two countries' governments 
and private enterprise to promote economic, social, and 
commercial development along the Costa Rican-Panamanian border. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

