<F P=101> CUBA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Welcomes U.S. Recognition of Country's </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry Welcomes U.S. Recognition of Country's </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
Antidrug   Efforts 

<F P=102> PA2705144294 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 1639 GMT 24 May 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2705144294 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>
BFN 

  [Text] Havana, 24 May (NOTIMEX) -- The Cuban Foreign 
Ministry today favorably reacted to an official U.S. report 
acknowledging the struggle the Havana Government has been waging 
against drug trafficking. Miguel Alfonso, a Cuban Foreign 
Ministry spokesman, referring to the U.S. State Department 
report issued last week, told the media: "It is belated, but we 
welcome it." 
  The spokesman said that the Foreign Ministry does not yet 
have any official analysis of the document, which is being 
analyzed by the Directorate of Multilateral Affairs. Alfonso 
announced, though, that this "recognition" of Cuba's official 
policy for the control of drug trafficking "is somewhat belated." 
  The U.S. State Department report pointed out "efforts the 
Cuban Government has made to prevent drug trafficking in its 
territorial waters and air space." The document also praised 
the steps the Caribbean nation has taken in this direction and 
noted that the Cuban authorities have reinforced their 
antidrug-trafficking struggle. The Cuban spokesman stated: "Our 
government's policy on the struggle against drug trafficking is 
long-lived." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

