<H3> <TI>   Involvement of Ciudad Juarez Firms in Money Laundering Probed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Involvement of Ciudad Juarez Firms in Money Laundering Probed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   94WB0038H Mexico City EXCELSIOR in Spanish 26 Apr 94 STATES 
Section pp 1, 4 </F>

<F P=103> 94WB0038H </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City EXCELSIOR </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by Manuel Cabrera] </F>
  [Excerpt] Ciudad Juarez, Chihuahua, 25 April--Business 
firms established here for some time could be involved in the 
"laundering of money" originating in the drug traffic. 
Therefore, the Attorney General's Office (PGR) is investigating 
the activities of at least three companies. This announcement 
was made today by the director of the National Association of 
Manufacturers (Canacintra), Miguel Angel Calderon Rodriguez. 
  He indicated that the department has located money from the 
drug traffic in commercial firms, but not in the manufacturing 
sector. 
  He cautioned that companies proven to have connections with 
that illicit activity will have their membership in Canacintra 
canceled immediately. 
  The state attorney, Francisco Molina Ruiz, declared that 
drug 
trafficking rings have infiltrated several areas of society, 
including the business-owning sector. 
  He noted that, two weeks ago, the U.S. agency fighting drugs 
(DEA) in El Paso, Texas, seized five tons of cocaine and 
arrested eight presumed drug traffickers, including the owner of 
the Jomar chain of stationery stores, Joel Omar Chavez Quezada. 
  Nevertheless, the attorney claimed not to know the names of 
the firms presumably implicated in laundering money representing 
the proceeds from dealing in that alkaloid. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

