<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Narcotics Roundup for 28 May-1 June </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Narcotics Roundup for 28 May-1 June </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0206015694 </F>
<F P=103> LD0206015694 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
fileworthy reports from 28 May-1 June on counternarcotics 
operations in countries monitored by FBIS London Bureau. 
Sources are given in parentheses at the end of each report. 
<H5>  Algeria </H5>
  Customs officiers at Algiers port confiscated 70 kg of hemp 
on 1 June from an immigrant here on his one-month holiday who 
wanted to smuggle the hemp from Algeria to Marseille. (Algiers 
ENTV Television Network in Arabic 1900 GMT 1 Jun 94) 
<H5>  Former Yugoslav Republic Of Macedonia </H5>
  Police in Skopje discovered and confiscated 32 kilograms of 
heroin from a Volkswagen van belonging to Arif Ismaili of Skopje 
on 26 May. The raid took place near the Bellevue hotel on the 
outskirts of the city. 
  According to a police report, the heroin was transported 
from 
Istanbul via the so-called new Balkan east-west land corridor 
and was supposed to be smuggled to Scandinavia through Bulgaria, 
Macedonia, Albania and Italy. (Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service 
in Serbo-Croatian 0838 GMT 28 May 94) 
<H5>  Kyrgyzstan </H5>
  A large batch of opium has been confiscated by Kyrgyz 
security agents on the Kyrgyz-Tajik border. Information about 
the planned drug-trafficking operation was provided to the 
Kyrgyz security services by a confidential source. (Moscow 
ITAR-TASS in English 0917 GMT 1 Jun 94) 
<H5>  Tajikistan </H5>
  In the first 4 months of this year Tajikistan's law 
enforcement agencies destroyed opium poppy on about 164 
hectares, largely in Leninabad region in the country's north. 
  According to data available to the law enforcers, the 
transit 
of narcotics to CIS countries and Europe through Tajikistan has 
considerably increased of late. Narcotics are smuggled largely 
across Tajikistan's border with Afghanistan that lies through 
Gorny Badakhshan, where the terrain is arduous and there are no 
technical installations along the border. (Moscow INTERFAX in 
English 1518 GMT 28 May 94) 

</TEXT>

