<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> BOLIVIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Views Plan To Tighten Controls on Precursors </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official Views Plan To Tighten Controls on Precursors </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2805033594 Cochabamba LOS TIEMPOS in Spanish 22 May 94 p A8 </F>
<F P=103> PY2805033594 </F>
<F P=104>  Cochabamba LOS TIEMPOS </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] La Paz, 21 May (LOS TIEMPOS) -- The National Social 
Defense Secretariat reported here today (21 May) that a 
"National Border Control Program" will be implemented to monitor 
the import and export of chemical precursors in Bolivia. 
  Victor Hugo Canelas, under secretary for controlled 
substances, noted that the program is still under study and will 
be implemented all year round in regions and zones of the 
country vulnerable to the illegal drug trade. 
  Canelas noted that the program the government is determined 
to implement in the short term will be supported by the United 
Nations and by countries that are "major producers" of chemical 
substances. 
  Canelas added that the program will consolidate logistical 
support for customs checkpoints in border areas having 
difficulties in carrying out their monitoring work. 
  Canelas said: "The proposal envisions training personnel, a 
modernization of communications and liaison, and the 
establishment of permanent customs and police checkpoints." 
  Canelas described remote areas located in the south 
(Yacuiba, 
Villazon), the west (Oruro, Charana, Desaguadero), and the 
Bolivian Amazon (Guayaramerin, Riberalta, and San Matias) as 
"vulnerable points" through which chemical products usually are 
introduced illegally into the country. 

</TEXT>

