<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> BOLIVIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   National Police Commander Supports Military Patrols in </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    National Police Commander Supports Military Patrols in </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
Chapare 

<F P=102>   PY3105001894 La Paz PRESENCIA in Spanish 21 May 94 p 7 </F>
<F P=103> PY3105001894 </F>
<F P=104>  La Paz PRESENCIA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>
BFN 

  [Text] National Police Commander General Luis Rocha said 
yesterday that his institution supports the military patrols 
being carried out in the Chapare region since early this week in 
accordance with constitutional regulations. 
  Rocha said: "The Armed Forces belong to the nation, and they 
have the constitutional right to be wherever they want to be in 
accordance with their needs." 
  He said, however, that this does not mean that the Special 
Antinarcotics Force (FELCN) is not capable of keeping order in 
the conflictive region of Chapare, in Cochabamba Department. 
  Asked about the alleged formation of irregular groups 
financed by drug trafficking, General Rocha said that the police 
intelligence services have not confirmed their presence, but 
that the situation is being investigated because of the latent 
threat of criminal groups linked to drug trafficking. 
  He also indicated that the investigation is being carried 
out 
jointly with Army intelligence. Answering reporters, Rocha 
said: "All the actions are of course being coordinated with the 
Armed Forces." 
  He added that the current situation does not demand an 
increase in the FELCN presence in the Chapare. On the contrary, 
he said, there are enough agents there to maintain control over 
any possible conflict. 

</TEXT>

