<H3> <TI>   Commentary Critical of U.S. Radar Decision </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Commentary Critical of U.S. Radar Decision </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0106023994 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 1200 GMT 31 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0106023994 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>

<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Commentary by (Antonio Paneso); from "Caracol's 0600 to </F>
0900" newscast] 
  [Text] International treaties are usually agreements 
benefiting two parties; one party cannot decide when to comply 
and when not to. It seems that this is the case now with an 
agreement signed by the United States and Colombia on bases for 
the surveillance of drug trafficking. 
  In this case it was clear that Colombia rendered a service 
to 
the United States and not the other way around. It would be 
preferable for our policy to be increasingly independent, 
because those installations are not useful even for monitoring 
civilian air traffic in Colombia, rather for rendering service 
only to U.S. addicts [viciosos]. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

